title: Grateful Dead Live at Cumberland County Civic Center on 1982-09-17
description:
Set 1:
Bertha-> Promised Land, Candyman-> CC Rider, Althea, Me & My Uncle-> Big River, Dupree's Diamond Blues, It's All Over Now, West L.A. Fadeaway, Throwing Stones, Deal

Set 2:
Touch Of Gray-> Women Are Smarter, High Time, Estimated Prophet-> Eyes Of The World-> Drums-> Spanish Jam-> The Other One-> Goin' Down The Road Feelin' Bad-> Morning Dew-> Sugar Magnolia, Encore: U.S. Blues

reviews.review_text:
Post-Drums is what keeps us all coming back This is a fantastic recording of a show that has some spectacular peaks and is never less than journeyman good. Material-wise, the biggest downside is the raft of new material: West L.A., Throwing Stones, and Touch of Grey. These are all early, undercooked versions, so they, along with underwhelming versions of Deal and Women are Smarter, give the show a fairly significant lull at its mid-point.

Playing-wise, the biggest downside, particularly post-drums, is Lesh's tendency to all but disappear in between incendiary flashes of staggering brilliance. It made me think of a bullfight: there are long pauses as the bull backs off, circles around, and decides how to attack next; then the attack is on and fantastically exciting action unfolds. For all the excitement, though, Lesh's on-again off-again theatrics come across as kind of weird and a little off-putting, but when Phil attacks it is truly wonderful.

Set one is engagingly good without being at any point truly great. Highlights for me were Candyman and Althea. Set two's so-so start of Touch>Smarter is immediately swept away by an excellent version of High Time. Whenever this song comes up I find myself mentally preparing for mumbled lyrics, sour notes, and other kinds of musical mayhem, so it's always refreshing when the version not only gets a clean delivery but also silences the joint with stupefying virtuosity.

Estimated/Eyes gets a better-than-average-but-still-fairly-routine delivery. Drums is drums, and on this recording the last few minutes get cut.

Finally we get to the meat of the matter: Space > Spanish Jam-> TOO-> GDTRFB-> AM Dew-> Sugar Mag. Garcia noodles nicely for a couple of minutes, Weir joins in as Garcia starts drifting into Other One noodling while working his way through an array of pedals and knobs. At about 4:45 Lesh plays a few notes, but then drops out. My sense is that he was having equipment issues at this point. A minute later, with the problem apparently fixed, they start into Spanish Jam, Everything, though, still ain't right and Lesh disappears for another bit. This kills all momentum on the Spanish Jam and it peters out as the jam morphs back into Other One riffs. Then Phil's back and The Other One heats up a bit. Then Lesh drops out again. The crowd calls out to him! He responds! Whatever the problem was it is now truly solved, and Lesh comes stomping in like Godzilla. Everyone responds with roiling disturbation. A brief but intense bloody moil ensues! Now that Phil has proven his readiness with some psychedelic rowdiness they take the jam down to quietude in order to prepare for the exquisite tension of a well-introduced Other One. When they finally hit the perfect moment for the Lesh-Bomb, Phil absolutely nukes it. The between-verse jam features a strong build-up to boiling intensity led by Garcia. Weir's playing pushes the intensity-envelope nicely, and Lesh creates a vibrant floor to it all. He's a bit low-key in comparison to the ruckus he kicked up earlier, but he still adds some octane the the jamming. The drop-off into GDTRFB comes faster than felt right; but Lesh was laying back after the 2nd verse so Garcia moves things along. The GDTRFB is a brisk Garcia-dominated run-through. It's nice to hear, a welcome transition between The Other One and Morning Dew, and it doesn't let the show's fire dim in the slightest. But it's not a notworthy rendition in its own right. Lesh lays way back for the entire song.

With the arrival of Morning Dew we get Lesh back again, in a big way. The first six minutes of this version are all brawny muscle from Lesh and gnarly wailing from Garcia. The middle jam is everything that jam ought to be: deeply inspirational and absolutely blistering. The whole place is in the palm of their hands as Garcia croons the outro lyrics. Gorgeous! Lesh, however, has decided it's time to take another break. He's very quiet, very unobtrusive, for a solid couple of minutes in there, during Garcia's vocals and then for the first minute of the final jam. Lesh giveth, Lesh takesh away. He surfaces, finally, for the final minute of what is basically a bare 2-minute Dew jam. wha happened?

Coming to the rescue of this shortish Dew is a robust romp through Sugar Magnolia. Phil phucking phlattens the joint with his two bombs at the end of vocals, and then punctuates the ensuing jam with throbbing, stabbing, slapping, bucking, and bombing. All hell breaks loose as they take the jam around a second time. The Thunder Gods Speak. Awesome.

This show is famous on the basis of the post-drums sequence, and deservedly so. In spite of some on-and-off behavior from Lesh, the rest of the band is in top form; so every time Lesh unleashes his inner beast the music becomes transcendently compelling . The peak moments, and there are several, are hair-raising in their intensity. The secret ingrediant is, of course, Maine.
